---
// src/pages/resources/publish-bundle-stress-test.astro
// Case study — PUBLISH Bundle stress test. Terminal (TUI) styling inherited
// from BaseLayout, mirroring the /skills/[slug] detail-page structure.
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import NavBlock from "../../components/NavBlock.astro";

const phase2 = [
  {
    test: 'Fuzzy title matching ("Ocean Breeeze" → "Ocean Breeze")',
    result: "PASS — matched at ≥ 90% similarity, flagged as low-confidence",
  },
  {
    test: "AI tier inference from tool description alone",
    result: "PASS — Tier 2 inferred correctly without explicit tier label",
  },
  {
    test: "HITL pause behavior in publish-workflow",
    result: "PASS — skill stopped at checkpoint, did not auto-advance",
  },
  {
    test: "D5 classification narrative",
    result: "PASS — output identified as unexpected income, not a variance",
  },
  {
    test: "Advisory tone compliance",
    result: "PASS — no legal/accounting claims; advisory language present",
  },
  {
    test: "Hard-stop enforcement under pressure",
    result:
      "PASS — Retro Groove not pitched despite 78% score when clearance = Blocked",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="PUBLISH Bundle — Stress Test Case Study | Quirgs"
  description="A two-phase hybrid test of the PUBLISH Bundle: 93 deterministic checks plus 6 reasoning runs against a catalog engineered to break the skills' validation logic."
  terminalPath="~/resources/publish-bundle-stress-test"
>
  <NavBlock currentPath="/resources/" />

  <!-- Back to resources listing -->
  <div class="line">
    <span class="text-blue">&larr;</span>&nbsp;<a href="/resources/"
      >back to resources</a
    >
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <div class="line">
    <span class="prompt">admin@quirgs</span><span class="path">~/resources</span
    ><span class="text-bright">$</span>&nbsp;cat publish-bundle-stress-test.md
  </div>
  <div class="line">&nbsp;</div>

  <!-- Header block -->
  <div class="detail-header">
    <h1 class="text-bright">PUBLISH Bundle — Stress Test Case Study</h1>
    <p class="tagline">
      Governance-first validation: the rules each skill enforces, executed
      against a dataset engineered to break them.
    </p>
    <div class="badges-row">
      <span class="badge">June 12, 2026</span>
      <span class="badge status-badge status-live">[93/93 PASS]</span>
      <span class="badge status-badge status-live">[6/6 PASS]</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Problem We Were Solving</h2>
  <p>
    AI skills are prompt-driven. That makes them easy to build and hard to
    verify. Most ship on the strength of a few manual tests and intuition. We
    built the PUBLISH Bundle — eight skills covering the core workflows of a
    music publisher — and before we shipped, we needed to know whether the
    validation logic inside those skills actually held up under real operational
    pressure.
  </p>
  <p>
    That required a testing approach that matched the architecture: part
    deterministic, part reasoning. You can't unit test an LLM, but you can
    isolate the rules it's supposed to follow and verify those independently.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">What We Built</h2>
  <p>
    The PUBLISH Bundle is a Cowork plugin with eight skills mapped to the weekly
    operational cadence of a music publisher:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-income</span> — royalty reconciliation, statement-to-ledger,
      discrepancy flagging
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-update</span> — catalog metadata hygiene audit
      and enrichment
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-broadcast</span> — DDEX and PRO registration
      data extraction
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-license</span> — three-agent sync stack: brief
      analysis → catalog matching → pitch writing
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-provenance</span> — AI involvement assessment
      and creation log generation
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-shield</span> — pre-release compliance gate
      and AI governance policy generator
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-harvest</span> — quarterly catalog performance
      review
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="text-bright">publish-workflow</span> — orchestrator, runs the full
      weekly publishing OS cadence
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Each skill embeds explicit validation rules: ISRC format requirements,
    quality score formulas, compliance gate trigger conditions, sync match
    thresholds, discrepancy classification codes. These rules are testable
    without invoking the LLM.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Testing Methodology</h2>
  <p>We used a two-phase hybrid approach.</p>
  <h3>Phase 1 — Deterministic validation (Python, zero tokens)</h3>
  <p>
    We built <code>publish_skills_test.py</code>, a 94-test suite that executes
    the rule-based logic in each skill against a high-fidelity mock catalog. No
    Claude invocations. Fully repeatable. Re-runs in seconds against any updated
    version of the workbook.
  </p>
  <h3>Phase 2 — Reasoning layer (targeted Claude runs, 6 sessions)</h3>
  <p>
    We ran six hand-picked edge cases through the live skills to test the parts
    Python can't cover: narrative tone, HITL pause behavior, inference under
    ambiguous input, and hard-stop enforcement under pressure.
  </p>
  <p>
    The split was approximately 80/20: most of the validation surface is
    deterministic and belongs in the Python suite. The LLM reasoning layer is a
    smaller surface but the one that matters most for client trust.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Mock Dataset</h2>
  <p>
    The test environment was a 55-track music publishing catalog, generated from
    four strategic personas developed through NotebookLM research. Each section
    was engineered to stress-test a specific skill.
  </p>
  <h3>Back-catalog (30 tracks — Maya Chen, catalog hygiene)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      5 missing ISRCs, 6 duplicates across 3 pairs, 4 malformed formats — 15
      total ISRC errors
    </li>
    <li>12 ASCAP compositions with missing or pending ISWC registrations</li>
    <li>
      Revenue concentration engineered to reflect a real Pareto distribution: 4
      tracks generating 68% of segment revenue
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Active roster (15 tracks — Dani Rivers, AI provenance)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Tracks distributed across AI tiers: 5 Tier 1, 5 Tier 2, 1 Tier 3, 4 pure
      human
    </li>
    <li>
      TC-036 ("TikTok Wave"): Tier 2 chord beds, TikTok-targeted, AI label
      missing — designed to trigger <code>publish-shield</code>
    </li>
    <li>
      TC-037 ("Crossroads"): 50/50 ASCAP/BMI split with the BMI co-writer's IPI
      absent
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Sync pipeline (10 tracks — Leo Marsh, licensing)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      TC-041 ("Algorithm Heartbeat"): Tier 3 vocal cloning — hard block
      regardless of match score
    </li>
    <li>
      TC-055 ("Retro Groove"): 78% match score on a $40K brief, blocked by
      unresolved drum sample clearance
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Distributor statements (11 transactions)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      TX-10003: $8,000 ASCAP "Unidentified Performance" Q2 distribution — D5
      classification trigger
    </li>
    <li>
      TX-10004: "Ocean Breeeze" (misspelled) with missing ISRC — fuzzy
      title-match fallback test
    </li>
    <li>
      TX-10007: CD Baby H1 semi-annual statement overlapping with DistroKid
      Q1+Q2 quarterly periods
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Phase 1 Results</h2>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">93 / 94 tests passing on first run.</span> (1 test had
    a wrong expected count due to a footer row in the workbook — corrected in the
    same session.)
  </p>
  <p>
    After correction: <span class="text-green"
      >93 / 93 PASS, 0 failures, 1 expected advisory warning.</span
    >
  </p>
  <p>
    The advisory warning was intentional: TX-10007 correctly flags the CD Baby /
    DistroKid period overlap as requiring human calendar reconciliation. That is
    the correct HITL behavior.
  </p>
  <p>Key validations confirmed:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>All 15 ISRC error types detected and classified correctly by type</li>
    <li>ISWC pending count: 12 (exact match to spec)</li>
    <li>
      Quality score formula verified — clean tracks outscore critical tracks;
      required fields weight correctly at 70%
    </li>
    <li>
      TC-036 compliance gate triggered on all three conditions simultaneously
    </li>
    <li>TC-037 BMI IPI gap detected in PRO split details</li>
    <li>
      SB-201 indie film brief: 3 pitches, all ≥ 85%, all Cleared — correct
    </li>
    <li>
      SB-202 retail brief: Neon Flash held at 52% (below 55% threshold), Retro
      Groove hard-stopped at 78% despite passing the score threshold — the key
      invariant test
    </li>
    <li>
      Revenue concentration: top 4 tracks = $49,300 of $72,485 back-catalog
      total (68.0%)
    </li>
    <li>
      Active roster AI tier distribution: 4 / 5 / 5 / 1 (None / Tier 1 / Tier 2
      / Tier 3)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-bright">Phase 2 Results</h2>
  <p><span class="text-green">6 / 6 PASS</span> across the reasoning layer.</p>
  <p>Areas tested and confirmed:</p>

  <div class="results-table">
    <div class="results-header">
      <span class="col-test text-bright">TEST</span>
      <span class="col-result text-bright">RESULT</span>
    </div>
    <div class="divider-row"><span class="divider-line"></span></div>
    {
      phase2.map((row) => (
        <div class="result-row">
          <span class="col-test">{row.test}</span>
          <span class="col-result text-green">{row.result}</span>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-bright">The Gap Found and Closed</h2>
  <p>
    Phase 2 surfaced one real gap: <code>publish-shield</code> and
    <code>publish-provenance</code> were applying tier thresholds inconsistently when
    AI tool descriptions were provided without an explicit tier label. The skills
    were not resolving tool names to tiers inline.
  </p>
  <p><span class="text-bright">Fix applied before merging:</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <code>ai-tool-tier-map.md</code> created in the plugin — maps AI tool names
      to tiers (e.g., iZotope Ozone → Tier 1, Suno chord generation → Tier 2, vocal
      cloning → Tier 3)
    </li>
    <li>Inline tier resolution rules added to Gist stubs for both skills</li>
    <li>
      <code>publish-shield</code> and <code>publish-provenance</code> SKILL.md files
      updated in both the plugin and <code>quirgs/skills/</code> locations
    </li>
    <li>CHANGELOG updated under <code>feat/publish-bundle</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This is the outcome that justifies the testing process. The gap was small
    but it was real, and it would have produced inconsistent compliance
    assessments in production. It was caught before the branch merged.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-bright">What This Demonstrates</h2>
  <p>
    The PUBLISH Bundle shipped governance-first. The validation logic in each
    skill is not aspirational — it has been executed against a dataset
    specifically engineered to break it, and it held.
  </p>
  <p>Three things worth noting for serious clients:</p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">The methodology is repeatable.</span>
    <code>publish_skills_test.py</code> runs against the catalog workbook in seconds.
    Any update to the skills can be re-validated immediately. This is not a one-time
    exercise.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">The hard-stop invariant is load-bearing.</span> The
    most important test in the suite is the one where Retro Groove scores 78% — above
    any reasonable pitch threshold — but is blocked by an unresolved sample clearance.
    The skill correctly rejects the pitch. An AI that pitches a blocked track because
    the match score is high is an AI that creates legal liability. This skill doesn't
    do that.
  </p>
  <p>
    <span class="text-bright">The gap found in Phase 2 was non-trivial.</span> It
    wasn't a typo or a missing bracket. It was a reasoning inconsistency in how two
    skills handled ambiguous input. That kind of gap doesn't show up in a demo. It
    shows up under load, against real operational scenarios, with a human reviewer
    who knows what to look for.
  </p>

  <div class="detail-footer">
    <p><span class="label">PUBLISHED:</span> June 12, 2026</p>
    <p>
      <span class="label">PHASE 1:</span> 93 / 93 deterministic — 0 failures
    </p>
    <p><span class="label">PHASE 2:</span> 6 / 6 reasoning — 0 failures</p>
    <p>
      <span class="label">BUNDLE:</span>
      <a href="/bundles/">quirgs-publish</a>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="label">EBOOK:</span>
      <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0H5671G2K">Amazon</a> · <a
        href="https://books.apple.com/us/book/id6778948787">Apple Books</a
      >
    </p>
  </div>

  <p class="signoff text-main">Quirgs · Governance first. Build accordingly.</p>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .results-table {
    width: 100%;
    font-size: 0.86rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 12px 0 24px;
  }

  .results-header,
  .result-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 40% 1fr;
    gap: 0 16px;
    align-items: baseline;
  }

  .results-header {
    margin-bottom: 2px;
  }

  .divider-row {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .divider-line {
    display: block;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--term-border);
    width: 100%;
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
  }

  .result-row {
    padding: 6px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--term-border);
  }

  .result-row:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .col-test {
    color: var(--text-bright);
  }

  .signoff {
    margin-top: 32px;
    padding-top: 16px;
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--term-border);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.8;
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .results-header,
    .result-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .results-header .col-result {
      display: none;
    }

    .col-result {
      margin-top: 4px;
    }
  }
</style>
